	  <texsupport xmlns="" href="../LinearAlgebraTeXSupport.xml"/>
	  <title>Equality of <math xmlns="">
         <latex>n</latex>
      </math>-tuples.</title>
	  <caption xmlns="">Equality of <math>
         <latex>n</latex>
      </math>-tuples.</caption>
	  <showme>
		    <statement.showme>
			      <para xmlns="">
            <para.body>Determine which of the following pairs of tuples are equal.</para.body>
         </para>
			      <ol xmlns="">
				        <li>
               <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>(4,1,-6,3)</latex>
                     </math> and <math>
                        <latex>(4,1,-6,3)</latex>
                     </math>
                  </para.body>
               </para>
            </li>
				        <li>
               <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>(1,0,3)</latex>
                     </math> and <math>
                        <latex>(1,0,0,3)</latex>
                     </math>
                  </para.body>
               </para>
            </li>
				        <li>
               <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>(1,3,2)</latex>
                     </math> and <math>
                        <latex>(6-5,2+1,3-1)</latex>
                     </math>
                  </para.body>
               </para>
            </li>
				        <li>
               <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>(1,2,1,2)</latex>
                     </math> and <math>
                        <latex>(2,1,2,1)</latex>
                     </math>
                  </para.body>
               </para>
            </li>
			      </ol>
		    </statement.showme>
		    <answer.showme xmlns="">
         <answer.showme.block>
            <answer.showme.block.body>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>To tell if two tuples are equal, we need to check if the numbers in matching positions are the same. Letâ€™s begin with the first pair:</para.body>
               </para>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>1. These two 4-tuples are equal: the numbers in matching positions are the same.</para.body>
               </para>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>2. The first tuple is a 3-tuple, while the second tuple is a 4-tuple. Tuples of distinct size are never equal.</para.body>
               </para>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>3. These two 3-tuples are equal as the entries in matching positions are the same.</para.body>
               </para>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>4. The <math>
                        <latex>4</latex>
                     </math>-tuple <math>
                        <latex>(1,2,1,2)</latex>
                     </math> has a <math>
                        <latex>1</latex>
                     </math> as its first coordinate, whereas the <math>
                        <latex>4</latex>
                     </math>-tuple <math>
                        <latex>(2,1,2,1)</latex>
                     </math> has a <math>
                        <latex>2</latex>
                     </math> as its first coordinate. So the first coordinates are distinct, and this is enough to render the 4-tuples distinct. In this case we could alternatively have observed that the second, or the third, or the fourth coordinates are distinct.</para.body>
               </para>
		          </answer.showme.block.body>
         </answer.showme.block>
      </answer.showme>
	  </showme>
